===Etymology===
{{etyl|enm}}, from {{etyl|ang}} {{term|tun|tūn|enclosure, village|lang=ang}}, from {{etyl|gem-pro|en}} {{recons|tūnan||fence|lang=gem-pro}} (compare West Frisian {{term|tún|lang=fy}}, Dutch {{term|tuin||garden|lang=nl}}, German {{term|Zaun|lang=de}}, Danish/Swedish {{term|tun|lang=sv}}), from Gaulish {{term|dunon||hill, hillfort|lang=cel-gau}} (compare Welsh {{term|din||hill|lang=cy}}, Irish {{term|dún||fortress|lang=ga}}), from {{etyl|cel-pro|en}} {{recons|dūnom|lang=cel-pro}}, from {{etyl|ine-pro|en}} {{recons|dʰewh₂-||to finish, come full circle|lang=ine-pro}}, (compare Hittite tuhhušta'' 'it is finished'{{rfscript|Xsux}}, Latin {{term|funus|fūnus|burial|lang=la}}, Ancient Greek {{term|θνητός|tr=thnētos||mortal|lang=grc}}, {{term|θάνατος|tr=thanatos||death|lang=grc}}, ''thaneīn'' 'to die'{{rfscript|Grek}}, Sanskrit ''ádhvanīt'' 'he vanished'{{rfscript|Deva}}).

